<article xml:id="session9wks" label="8972">

  <title>MATH 142 Hands-On, Grades Up</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
     For workspace between exercises, print this worksheet or download to your device by clicking the printer icon.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <worksheet>

    <title>Session #9 (4.1 and 4.2)</title>

    <p>
      Directions: Answer each of the following as best you can. Feel free to discuss your thoughts about the questions with some peers around you. 
      For additional practice problems and explanations, refer to the Math 142 textbook which is free and can be downloaded as a PDF 
      at <url href="https://oaktrust.library.tamu.edu/items/03980291-5e85-4d2e-a742-961ac49666aa"> Texas A&amp;M The OAKTrust Digital Repository </url>.
      <!--'&' and '<' are exceptional characters and are instead authored as &lt; and &amp;. See 4.1.4.2-->
    </p>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>Getting Warmed Up and in the Right Mindset</title>


      <exercise workspace="1in">
        <introduction>
          <p>
            Complete the following antiderivative rules.
          </p>
        </introduction>

        <task workspace="1in">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Constant Rule:
              <m>\int k \, dx = </m> <fillin characters="10" />,
              where <m>k</m> is any real number.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>

        <task workspace="1in">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Power Rule:
              <m>\int x^n \, dx = </m> <fillin characters="10" />,
              where <m>n</m> is any real number with <m>n \neq -1</m>.
            </p>

            <p>
              Special Case:
              <m>\int \frac{1}{x}\,dx = </m><fillin characters="10" />
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>

        <task workspace="1in">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Exponential Rule:
              <m>\int b^x\,dx = </m> <fillin characters="10" />,
              where <m>b</m> is a positive real number.
            </p>

            <p>
              Special Case:
              <m>\int e^x\,dx = </m> <fillin characters="10" />
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>

        <task workspace="1in">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Sum/Difference Rule:
              <m>\int (f(x)\pm g(x))\,dx = </m> <fillin characters="10" />
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>

        <task workspace="1in">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Constant Multiple Rule:
              <m>\int kf(x)\,dx = </m> <fillin characters="10" /> where <m>k</m> is any real number.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>

      </exercise>

    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs>

      <title>Let Us Get Our Hands On</title>

      <exercise workspace="2in" number="1">
        <statement>
          <p>
            The most general antiderivative of
            <m>f'(x)=2x+e^x+6x^2</m>
            is
            <m>f(x)=</m> <fillin characters="15" />
          </p>

          <p>
            Use the space below to check your answer by differentiating your result.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>

      <exercise workspace="2in" number="2">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Find
            <m>\int (x^4-x^3+x^2)\,dx</m>.
          </p>

          <p>
            Check your answer by differentiating your result.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>

      <exercise workspace="2in" number="3">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Find
            <m>\int (5t^8-2t^4+t+3)\,dt</m>.
          </p>

          <p>
            Check your answer by differentiating your result.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>

      <exercise workspace="2in" number="4">

        <introduction>
          <p>
            Find the following indefinite integrals.
          </p>
        </introduction>

        <task workspace="1.5in">
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\int (7u^{3/2}+2u^{1/2})\,du</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>

        <task workspace="1.5in">
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\int (3x^{-2}-4x^{-3})\,dx</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>

        <task workspace="1.5in">
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\int \left(\frac{3}{x}+3^x\ln(3)+\frac{6}{x^{2/3}}\right)\,dx</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>

        <task workspace="1.5in">
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\int \frac{3x^2+4x+1}{2x}\,dx</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>

        <task workspace="1.5in">
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\int \frac{x^4-6x^3+e^x\sqrt{x}}{\sqrt{x}}\,dx</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>

      </exercise>

      <exercise workspace="2in" number="5">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Find the constant of integration <m>C</m> for
            <m>f'(x)=5e^x-3x^2</m>
            given
            <m>f(0)=6</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>

      <exercise workspace="2in" number="6">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Find the specific antiderivative of
            <m>f'(r)=r^2-2r+\frac{1}{r}</m>
            given
            <m>f(1)=\frac{4}{3}</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>

      <exercise workspace="2in" number="7">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Find the specific antiderivative of
            <m>g'(t)=(5-t)(3+7\sqrt{t^3})</m>
            given
            <m>g(4)=220</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>

      <exercise workspace="2in" number="8">

        <introduction>
          <p>
            For each indefinite integral below, find an appropriate substitution,
            rewrite the integral in terms of the new variable, and then compute
            the indefinite integral.
          </p>
        </introduction>

        <task workspace="2in">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Given
              <m>\int x^2(x^3+1)^4\,dx</m>,
              let
              <m>u=</m> __________
              and
              <m>du=</m> __________.
            </p>

            <p>
              Rewrite the integral in terms of <m>u</m> and evaluate.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>

        <task workspace="2in">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Given
              <m>\int \frac{6x}{\sqrt{1-x^2}}\,dx</m>,
              let
              <m>u=</m> __________
              and
              <m>du=</m> __________.
            </p>

            <p>
              Rewrite the integral in terms of <m>u</m> and evaluate.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>

        <task workspace="2in">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Given
              <m>\int (x^2+1)e^{2x^3+6x-8}\,dx</m>,
              let
              <m>u=</m> __________
              and
              <m>du=</m> __________.
            </p>

            <p>
              Rewrite the integral in terms of <m>u</m> and evaluate.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>

      </exercise>

      <exercise workspace="1.5in" number="9">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Find
            <m>\int 2e^{8x}\,dx</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>

      <exercise workspace="1.5in" number="10">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Find
            <m>\int (16x^2+2e^{8x})\,dx</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>

    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs>

      <title>Now Grades Go Up</title>

      <exercise workspace="2in" number="1">
        <statement>
          <p>
            A company has a marginal revenue function given by
            <m>R'(x)=\frac{600}{2x+1}</m>
            dollars per item when <m>x</m> items are sold.
            Find the company's revenue function when <m>x</m> items are sold.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>

      <exercise workspace="2in" number="2">
        <statement>
          <p>
            The marginal cost for a company when <m>x</m> items are produced can be modeled by
            <m>C'(x)=\ln(2)(0.02x)2^{0.01x^2}</m> dollars per item when <m>x</m> items are produced.
            If it costs <m>\$102</m> to produce 10 items,
            what is the cost to produce 20 items?
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>

    </paragraphs>

  </worksheet>

</article>

</pretext>